model_explanation: if Sam only gave Bill bananas, then it contradicts the idea that he also gave Bill grapes.
if Sam only gave Mary apples, it means apples were exclusively for Mary and thus conflicts with giving apples to Ellen as well.
giving apples only to Sue means no one else should receive them, so giving apples to Tom contradicts that.
if Bill only got grapes, it follows that he didn’t get oranges, so they are consistent.
if Bill only got apples, it means he got no other fruit, so he didn’t get bananas, making this entailed.
if Sue only got apples, she didn’t get other fruits, so she must not have gotten bananas, thus they are consistent.
if the oranges were exclusively given to Ellen, it’s entailed that Tom couldn’t have received any oranges.
if only Tom got apples, it naturally follows that Mary didn’t get any apples, so the second statement is consistent with the first.
if only Tom received apples, then giving apples to Bill as well contradicts that exclusivity.
if Sue was the only recipient of bananas, then it follows that Tom didn’t get any bananas.
